"@londumas - Thanks for the bug report!\n\nFor reference, the API docs for `Minuit.minos` are [here](http://iminuit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/api.html#iminuit.Minuit.minos) and the tests are in [iminuit/tests/test_iminuit.py](https://github.com/iminuit/iminuit/blob/master/iminuit/tests/test_iminuit.py).\n\nLooks like there is no test that calls `minos` passing a `sigma`.\nThere's only one test passing `sigma`  to `mncontour`: `test_mncontour_sigma`.\n\n@londumas - Can you contribute a test that shows the issue, i.e. runs a minimal example and has an assert statement at the end on what you expect, that currently fails.\nThat would be the first step, then the next one is to look at the implementation and fix it.\n\nI don't have time, sorry.\nHelp welcome!\n\n\nok, I am writing it. interestingly, it works in 1.1.1\n\n\n@londumas - Thank you!\n\n\nHere is a working example. Could you have a look ?\n\nThe idea is to try to get the error on a Gaussian filled with numpy.rand.normal\n\n[test_error_minos.txt](https://github.com/iminuit/iminuit/files/356626/test_error_minos.txt)\n\n\nI have a way simplier example here:\r\n```\r\nimport iminuit\r\n\r\ndef f(x):\r\n    return x**2\r\n\r\nm= iminuit.Minuit(f)\r\nm.migrad()\r\n==> error = +/- 1\r\nm.minos()\r\n==> error = +/- 2\r\nm.minos(sigma=2)\r\n==> error = +/- 3\r\nm.minos(sigma=3)\r\n```\n\nWhat more can I do to have this issue fixed ?\n\n\nThe bug might be in iminuit/_libiminuit.pyx,\r\n\r\nself.pyfcn.set_up(oldup * sigma * sigma) at line 569\r\n\r\ncould you have a look, it could be cool to fix that.\r\n\n\nsomething might have happen here:\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/iminuit/iminuit/commit/cf718b74c24ed79e96b186d4cec556b2b1ceac8d\r\n\r\nbecause there is no problem iniminuit==1.2 \r\n\r\n@chrisburr could you look what changed you have made that broke the minos sigma errors ?"